    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, the mathematical differences between Lasso (L1) and Ridge (L2) regularization are rooted in their respective penalty terms and how they influence the optimization problem.\n\nLasso regularization adds a penalty term equal to the absolute value of the coefficients, which is |β|. This absolute value penalty is non-differentiable at zero, which can lead to coefficients being exactly zero. The optimization problem for Lasso becomes:\n\nminimize (1/2n) * ||y - Xβ||^2 + λ * Σ|β_i|\n\nThis penalty term encourages sparsity in the coefficients because it can completely eliminate some of them, especially when the corresponding feature is not very important.\n\nOn the other hand, Ridge regularization adds a penalty term equal to the square of the coefficients, which is β^2. This penalty term is differentiable everywhere, which means it never drives coefficients exactly to zero but rather shrinks them towards zero. The optimization problem for Ridge is:\n\nminimize (1/2n) * ||y - Xβ||^2 + λ * Σβ_i^2\n\nThe quadratic penalty in Ridge encourages smaller coefficients, but because it does not have a non-differentiable point, it does",
      "source": "target",
